Introduction to Computer Vision: Plant Seedlings Classification¶

Problem Statement¶

Context¶

In recent times, the field of agriculture has been in urgent need of modernizing, since the amount of manual work people need to put in to check if plants are growing correctly is still highly extensive. Despite several advances in agricultural technology, people working in the agricultural industry still need to have the ability to sort and recognize different plants and weeds, which takes a lot of time and effort in the long term. The potential is ripe for this trillion-dollar industry to be greatly impacted by technological innovations that cut down on the requirement for manual labor, and this is where Artificial Intelligence can actually benefit the workers in this field, as the time and energy required to identify plant seedlings will be greatly shortened by the use of AI and Deep Learning. The ability to do so far more efficiently and even more effectively than experienced manual labor, could lead to better crop yields, the freeing up of human inolvement for higher-order agricultural decision making, and in the long term will result in more sustainable environmental practices in agriculture as well.

Objective¶

The aim of this project is to Build a Convolutional Neural Netowrk to classify plant seedlings into their respective categories.

Data Dictionary¶

The Aarhus University Signal Processing group, in collaboration with the University of Southern Denmark, has recently released a dataset containing images of unique plants belonging to 12 different species.

  • The dataset can be download from Olympus.

  • The data file names are:

    • images.npy
    • Labels.csv

  • Due to the large volume of data, the images were converted to the images.npy file and the labels are also put into Labels.csv, so that you can work on the data/project seamlessly without having to worry about the high data volume.

  • The goal of the project is to create a classifier capable of determining a plant's species from an image.

List of Species

  • Black-grass
  • Charlock
  • Cleavers
  • Common Chickweed
  • Common Wheat
  • Fat Hen
  • Loose Silky-bent
  • Maize
  • Scentless Mayweed
  • Shepherds Purse
  • Small-flowered Cranesbill
  • Sugar beet

def plot_images(images,labels):
  num_classes=10                                                                  # Number of Classes
  categories=np.unique(labels)
  keys=dict(labels['Label'])                                                      # Obtaing the unique classes from y_train
  rows = 3                                                                        # Defining number of rows=3
  cols = 4                                                                        # Defining number of columns=4
  fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))                                               # Defining the figure size to 10x8
  for i in range(cols):
      for j in range(rows):
          random_index = np.random.randint(0, len(labels))                        # Generating random indices from the data and plotting the images
          ax = fig.add_subplot(rows, cols, i * rows + j + 1)                      # Adding subplots with 3 rows and 4 columns
          ax.imshow(images[random_index, :])                                      # Plotting the image
          ax.set_title(keys[random_index])
  plt.show()

Observations

Plant Seedling Classification Project Summary¶

Updated Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) Observations¶

  1. Visual Differences Between Plant Categories:

    • Leaf Shape and Structure: There's significant variation across species. For instance, Fat Hen displays broad, diamond-shaped leaves, while Black-grass has thin, elongated grass-like leaves. Shepherds Purse shows a distinct rosette pattern.
    • Color Variations: While most plants exhibit shades of green, the intensity varies. Charlock appears to have a lighter, yellowish-green hue compared to the deeper green of Common Chickweed.
    • Growth Patterns: Some species like Shepherds Purse and Scentless Mayweed show a more spread-out growth pattern, while others like Common Chickweed appear more compact and clustered.
    • Leaf Texture: Variations in leaf surface are noticeable. For example, Fat Hen leaves appear smoother compared to the more textured surface of Charlock leaves.
    • Background Variation: The images show different backgrounds, ranging from bare soil to gravel and even man-made elements like measuring tools, which could impact model learning.

  2. Dataset Imbalance:

    • The dataset shows clear imbalance across different plant species.
    • Class Distribution:
      • Most represented class: Black-grass (263 samples)
      • Least represented class: Maize (221 samples)
    • Imbalance Ratio: The ratio of the most common to least common class is approximately 1.19:1, indicating a moderate imbalance.
    • Mid-range classes: Common Chickweed (245 samples), Fat Hen (240 samples)
    • This imbalance, while not extreme, could potentially bias the model towards over-represented classes.

  3. Image Quality and Standardization:

    • Image Size: All images are standardized to 128x128 pixels, providing consistency in input size for the model.
    • Image Clarity: Most images are clear and focused, but some (e.g., certain Black-grass samples) appear slightly blurred, which could affect feature extraction.

  4. Background Noise and Variability:

    • Soil Visibility: The amount of visible soil varies significantly between images, from almost none to very prominent.
    • Non-Plant Elements: Some images include measuring tools or other man-made objects, which could potentially confuse the model or provide unintended cues.

  5. Plant Growth Stages:

    • The seedlings are captured at various early growth stages, with some showing just the first leaves while others display more developed structures.
    • This variation in growth stages within each class adds complexity to the classification task but also makes the model more robust for real-world applications.

  6. Lighting Conditions:

    • There's noticeable variation in lighting across the dataset. Some images appear to be taken in bright, direct light, while others seem to be in more diffused or shadowed conditions.
    • This variation could help in developing a model that's more adaptable to different lighting conditions in the field.

  7. Potential Challenges for Classification:

    • Similar-looking species: Some species, like different types of grass (e.g., Black-grass and Loose Silky-bent), may be challenging to distinguish due to their similar appearance at the seedling stage.
    • Background interference: The varying backgrounds and presence of non-plant elements might make it difficult for the model to focus solely on the plant features.

These observations suggest that while the dataset provides a rich variety of plant seedling images, the model will need to be robust to handle variations in growth stage, lighting, background, and class imbalance. Data augmentation techniques and careful consideration of class weights during model training could be beneficial in addressing these challenges.

Resizing Images¶

  • As the size of the images is large, it may be computationally expensive to train on these larger images; therefore, it is preferable to reduce the image size from 128 to 64.

Data Normalization¶

Since the image pixel values range from 0-255, our method of normalization here will be scaling - we shall divide all the pixel values by 255 to standardize the images to have values between 0-1.

In [19]:
# Normalize the image pixels of train, test and validation data
X_train_normalized = X_train.astype('float32')/255.0
X_val_normalized = X_val.astype('float32')/255.0
X_test_normalized = X_test.astype('float32')/255.0

# Initializing a sequential model
model1 = Sequential()                             # Initialize a sequential model

# First convolutional layer
model1.add(Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding="same", input_shape=(64, 64, 3)))
# 128 filters, 3x3 kernel, ReLU activation, same padding, input shape 64x64x3

# Max pooling layer
model1.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2), padding='same'))
# 2x2 pool size with same padding

# Second convolutional and max-pooling layer
model1.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding="same"))
model1.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2), padding='same'))

# Third convolutional and max-pooling layer (already completed in your code)
model1.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding="same"))
model1.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2), padding='same'))

# Flatten layer
model1.add(Flatten())
# Flatten the output for dense layers

# Fully connected dense layer
model1.add(Dense(16, activation='relu'))
# 16 neurons with ReLU activation

model1.add(Dropout(0.3))

# Output layer
model1.add(Dense(12, activation='softmax'))
# 12 neurons (one for each class) with softmax activation

# Optimizer
opt = Adam()

# Compile the model
model1.compile(optimizer=opt, loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
# Adam optimizer, categorical crossentropy loss (for multi-class classification), accuracy metric

# Generate model summary
model1.summary()

Model Performance Improvement¶

Reducing the Learning Rate:

Hint: Use ReduceLRonPlateau() function that will be used to decrease the learning rate by some factor, if the loss is not decreasing for some time. This may start decreasing the loss at a smaller learning rate. There is a possibility that the loss may still not decrease. This may lead to executing the learning rate reduction again in an attempt to achieve a lower loss.

In [29]:
# Code to monitor val_accuracy
learning_rate_reduction = ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor='val_accuracy',
                                            patience=3,
                                            verbose=1,
                                            factor=0.5,
                                            min_lr=0.00001)

from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Conv2D, MaxPooling2D, BatchNormalization, Flatten, Dense, Dropout
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam

# Initializing a sequential model
model2 = Sequential()
# First conv layer with 64 filters and kernel size 3x3, padding 'same' provides the output size same as the input size
model2.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding="same", input_shape=(64, 64, 3)))
# Max pooling to reduce the size of output of first conv layer
model2.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2), padding='same'))
model2.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding="same"))
model2.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2), padding='same'))
model2.add(BatchNormalization())
# Flattening the output of the conv layer after max pooling to make it ready for creating dense connections
model2.add(Flatten())
# Adding a fully connected dense layer with 16 neurons
model2.add(Dense(16, activation='relu'))
# Adding dropout with dropout_rate=0.3
model2.add(Dropout(0.3))
# Output layer with 12 neurons and softmax activation for multi-class classification
model2.add(Dense(12, activation='softmax'))
# Initialize Adam Optimizer
opt = Adam()
# Compile model
model2.compile(optimizer=opt, loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
# Generating the summary of the model
model2.summary()

Final Model¶

Comment on the final model you have selected and use the same in the below code to visualize the image.

We developed and evaluated three different models for the plant seedling classification task:

  1. Basic CNN Model:
  • Test Accuracy: 0.5263
  • This model provided a baseline performance but struggled with the complexity of the classification task.
  1. CNN Model with Data Augmentation:
  • Test Accuracy: 0.7368
  • The addition of data augmentation significantly improved the model's performance, demonstrating the importance of data diversity in training.
  1. VGG16 Transfer Learning Model:
  • Test Accuracy: 0.8700
  • This model achieved the best performance, with an overall accuracy of 87% across the 12 classes.

Based on these results, the VGG16 model clearly outperforms the other two models and is selected as the best performing model for this plant seedling classification task. Its superior performance can be attributed to:

  • The power of transfer learning, leveraging pre-trained weights from a large dataset (ImageNet).
  • A deeper architecture capable of learning more complex features.

Effective fine-tuning on our specific dataset.

Actionable Insights and Business Recommendations¶

  1. Model Selection and Performance:
  • Insight: The VGG16 transfer learning model significantly outperformed the basic CNN and data-augmented CNN, achieving 87% accuracy compared to 52.63% and 73.68% respectively.
  • Recommendation: Implement the VGG16 model as the core of an automated plant seedling classification system. This will provide the most accurate results for farmers and agricultural businesses.
  1. Data Augmentation Impact:
  • Insight: Data augmentation improved model accuracy by over 20%, highlighting the importance of diverse training data.
  • Recommendation: Continuously collect and augment data to improve model robustness. Implement a system for farmers to contribute new images, expanding the dataset over time.
  1. Class-Specific Performance:
  • Insight: The model performs exceptionally well on some classes (e.g., Class 7 with 100% recall) but struggles with others (e.g., Class 0 with 38% recall).
  • Recommendation: Focus additional data collection and model fine-tuning efforts on underperforming classes. Develop class-specific modules for challenging plant species.
  1. Real-time Classification:
  • Insight: The model's high accuracy enables reliable real-time classification.
  • Recommendation: Develop a mobile application for farmers to instantly identify plant seedlings in the field. This can aid in early weed detection and targeted treatment.
  1. Integration with Precision Agriculture:
  • Insight: Accurate plant identification is a cornerstone of precision agriculture.
  • Recommendation: Integrate the classification model with automated farming equipment for targeted herbicide application, reducing chemical usage and costs while improving crop yields.
  1. Environmental Impact:
  • Insight: Precise plant identification can lead to more efficient use of agricultural resources.
  • Recommendation: Market the system as an eco-friendly solution that reduces herbicide use and promotes sustainable farming practices.
  1. Economic Benefits:
  • Insight: Automated classification can significantly reduce labor costs and improve efficiency.
  • Recommendation: Develop a cost-benefit analysis tool for farmers, demonstrating the potential savings and yield improvements from implementing the system.
  1. Continuous Learning and Improvement:
  • Insight: The model's performance varies across different plant species.
  • Recommendation: Implement a feedback mechanism where users can report misclassifications, enabling continuous model improvement and adaptation to local conditions.
  1. Scalability and Adaptability:
  • Insight: Transfer learning's success suggests the model could be adapted to other related tasks.
  • Recommendation: Explore expanding the system to classify plant diseases, assess crop health, and estimate yields, creating a comprehensive crop management solution.
  1. User Training and Support:
  • Insight: The technology's effectiveness depends on proper use by farmers.
  • Recommendation: Develop a comprehensive training program and user-friendly interface to ensure farmers can effectively integrate the technology into their workflows.

By implementing these recommendations, agricultural businesses can leverage this advanced plant seedling classification model to significantly improve efficiency, reduce costs, and move towards more sustainable and precise farming practices. The high accuracy of the VGG16 model provides a solid foundation for building a reliable and impactful agricultural technology solution.*
